{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534349"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:45:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:45:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14920"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14920"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.91,0.06,0.01,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7608"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59371"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7608"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14920"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44777"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4259"},{"type":"tags","id":"4264"},{"type":"tags","id":"4607"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18612"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59371"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit following a house fire. He has sustained full-thickness burns to his anterior chest, abdomen and both upper limbs, estimated at 40% of total body surface area. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He was intubated at the scene due to airway concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears critically unwell. His pulse rate is 135/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate controlled on ventilator, SpO2 98% on FiO2 0.4, and temperature 35.8\u00b0C. His burns are charred and non-blanching. He has not passed any urine since admission two hours ago.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rapid fluid resuscitation","Urgent escharotomy","Insert nasogastric tube for feeding","Start prophylactic antibiotics","Commence noradrenaline infusion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe burns requiring immediate fluid resuscitation. The hypotension and tachycardia indicate hypovolaemic shock, which is expected in major burns due to massive fluid shifts and capillary leak. The absence of urine output is concerning and indicates inadequate end-organ perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid fluid resuscitation\u003C/strong\u003E is the immediate priority. The Parkland formula (4mL/kg/%TBSA of crystalloid over 24 hours, with half given in the first 8 hours) should guide initial fluid requirements. Urine output should be monitored as the key indicator of adequate resuscitation, targeting 0.5-1.0 mL/kg/hour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoradrenaline infusion\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the underlying hypovolaemia. Vasopressors should be avoided until adequate fluid resuscitation has been achieved, as they may mask ongoing fluid requirements and compromise tissue perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProphylactic antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not routinely recommended in burns patients unless there are specific indicators of infection. The priority is establishing adequate fluid resuscitation and maintaining tissue perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscharotomy\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary if there is evidence of circumferential burns causing compartment syndrome or respiratory compromise, but this is not described in the scenario. The immediate priority is fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasogastric feeding\u003C/strong\u003E is important in burns patients and should be initiated early (within 24-48 hours), but it is not the most urgent priority in this situation where the patient is in hypovolaemic shock.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early fluid resuscitation using the Parkland formula (4mL/kg/%TBSA) or similar is crucial in major burns.","Urine output is the key indicator for adequacy of fluid resuscitation in burns patients."],"references":["Schaefer TJ, Nunez Lopez O. Burn Resuscitation and Management. [Updated 2023 Jan 23]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430795/","Regan A, Hotwagner DT. Burn Fluid Management. [Updated 2023 Jun 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534227/","Guilabert, P. et al. Fluid resuscitation management in patients with burns. British Journal of Anaesthesia, Volume 117, Issue 3, 284 - 296"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44777"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14920"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44777"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-07T11:57:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-07T11:58:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7608"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59371"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attribute